callChain.conditionalDependenciesToolTip:
Consider Conditional Dependencies - this option will limit the call chain to only include paths that are actually possible considering the entire call chain. For example, if a program accesses a certain file only when called from a particular job, then the path from the program to the file will only be included when that particular job is also part of the call chain.

This option should be enabled only for end-to-end call chains, i.e. your start (end) modules should actually be at the beginning (end) of the call chain. Otherwise, the result might be incomplete.

reachability.reachabilityContent:
A reachability block represents a dependency graph from one upper bound 
 (like job or stored procedure) to its lower bounds (like a table or file) via the modules in between. 
 It is created automatically and can be merged manually with other blocks. They help to understand and structure the technical dependencies of a system.
reachability.networkContent: A reachability network is a dependency graph, illustrating connections between all reachability blocks via shared lower bounds. Direction of the arrows indicate producer-consumer relationship i.e., A producer block writes into a shared lower bound, which is then consumed or read by the consumer block. Bi-directional connection means both the blocks are either producers or consumers or both.
reachability.networkSchedulerAdditionalContent: Additionally you can also see the actual job dependencies between the blocks by importing scheduler data under

reachability.commonLowerBound: What is a Common Lower Bound?
reachability.commonLowerBoundContent: Edges of the network are only created between reachability blocks when there is atleast one write access on one and a read access on the other reachability block. if two reachability blocks have only read access to the same lower bound, then it does not create any edge and hence not considered as common lower bound.
